When I was born in 2002, they thought naming me after the main character would be the ultimate tribute to their favourite franchise. They love Star Wars so much they had a room in our house dedicated to collectibles, spent thousands on replica lightsabers and went to every movie premiere in full costume. When I was little, it didn't matter because kids didn't get the reference yet. Elementary school was manageable because most kids hadn't seen the movies. Teachers would smile awkwardly when they read my name, but nobody made it a big deal. Then fourth grade happened and the revenge of the Sith came out. They just be there. At first it felt annoying. I remember thinking, can I just be sad alone for five minutes? But then something weird happened. It actually helped, like, way more than I expected. The rule became automatic in our house. If you saw someone tearing up, you didn't ask questions or try to fix it. You just joined them. Even when my friends came over. They Learned fast. Things got more intense when mom got diagnosed with cancer. I was in sixth grade and didn't really understand what that meant, but I knew it was bad from how quiet everyone got.
